<section id="intro">

<h2>4.1 Meaning and Definition</h2>

<p>
A <b>table</b> is a systematic arrangement of data in rows and columns.
Tabulation may be defined as the systematic arrangement of classified numerical data 
in rows and columns according to certain characteristics.
</p>

<p>
Tabulation expresses data in a concise and attractive form which can be easily understood 
and used for comparison. It enables an investigator to locate the desired information quickly.
</p>

<p>
Statistical tables make it possible to present a huge mass of data in a detailed and orderly form. 
It facilitates comparison and often reveals patterns in data that are otherwise not obvious.
</p>

<p>
Before tabulation, data are classified and then displayed under different columns and rows.
</p>

---

<h2>4.2 Difference Between Classification and Tabulation</h2>

<table>

<tr>
<th>Classification</th>
<th>Tabulation</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Process of grouping raw data according to characteristics.</td>
<td>Logical arrangement of data into rows and columns.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>First step in organizing data.</td>
<td>Second step in presenting data.</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>Condenses mass of data to identify similarities and differences.</td>
<td>Simplifies complex data for comparison.</td>
</tr>

</table>

---

<h2>4.3 Objectives / Advantages of Tabulation</h2>

<ul>

<li>Simplifies complex data for easy understanding.</li>

<li>Facilitates comparison of related facts.</li>

<li>Helps in computation of statistical measures like averages, dispersion and correlation.</li>

<li>Presents facts in minimum space and avoids repetition.</li>

<li>Useful for preparing graphs and diagrams.</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>4.4 Disadvantages of Tabulation</h2>

<ul>

<li>Requires skill and knowledge to arrange data properly.</li>

<li>Lack of description about the nature of data.</li>

<li>Important details may not be emphasized.</li>

<li>Data may be misinterpreted.</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>4.5 Characteristics of a Good Table</h2>

<ul>

<li>A table should match the objective of the statistical enquiry.</li>

<li>It should be simple and easy to understand.</li>

<li>Table size should fit the page properly.</li>

<li>Large figures should be rounded when necessary.</li>

<li>Units of measurement must be specified.</li>

<li>Rows and columns should follow logical order.</li>

<li>Totals should be shown clearly.</li>

<li>Footnotes and sources must be provided.</li>

<li>If data is too large, multiple tables should be used.</li>

</ul>

---

<h2>4.6 Parts of a Statistical Table</h2>

A statistical table consists of the following components:

<ul>

<li>Table Number</li>

<li>Title of the Table</li>

<li>Head Note</li>

<li>Captions (Column Headings)</li>

<li>Stubs (Row Headings)</li>

<li>Body</li>

<li>Footnotes</li>

<li>Source Note</li>

</ul>

<h3>Explanation</h3>

<p><b>Table Number:</b> Used for identification and reference.</p>

<p><b>Table Title:</b> A clear description of the table contents.</p>

<p><b>Head Note:</b> Explains units of measurement such as "in thousands".</p>

<p><b>Captions:</b> Column headings that explain column data.</p>

<p><b>Stubs:</b> Row headings describing row categories.</p>

<p><b>Body:</b> Contains the actual numerical data.</p>

<p><b>Footnotes:</b> Additional explanation for data items.</p>

<p><b>Source:</b> Indicates the origin of data.</p>

---

<h2>4.7 Types of Tabulation</h2>

<h3>1. Based on Number of Characteristics</h3>

<h4>Simple Table</h4>

<p>Contains data for only one characteristic.</p>

<div class="example">

<b>Example: Population by State</b>

<table>

<tr>
<th>State</th>
<th>Population</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>KA</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>AP</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>MP</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>UP</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

---

<h4>Complex Table</h4>

<p>Contains data for two or more characteristics.</p>

<div class="example">

<b>Two Way Table: Population by State and Sex</b>

<table>

<tr>
<th rowspan="2">State</th>
<th colspan="2">Population</th>
<th rowspan="2">Total</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<th>Males</th>
<th>Females</th>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>KA</td>
<td>-</td>
<td>-</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>AP</td>
<td>-</td>
<td>-</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>MP</td>
<td>-</td>
<td>-</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>UP</td>
<td>-</td>
<td>-</td>
<td>-</td>
</tr>

</table>

</div>

---

<h3>2. Based on Purpose</h3>

<h4>General Purpose Tables</h4>

<p>
These tables provide detailed information for general reference. 
Example: Census tables.
</p>

<h4>Special Purpose Tables</h4>

<p>
These tables provide summarized information for specific analysis such as percentages,
ratios and index numbers.
</p>

---

<h3>3. Based on Originality</h3>

<h4>Primary Tables</h4>

<p>
Contain original statistical data without modification.
Example: Rainfall or production records.
</p>

<h4>Derived Tables</h4>

<p>
Contain data derived from original tables such as percentages, averages and ratios.

</p>

</section>

